            "title": "Spatial interpolation and prediction of Gaussian and Max-stable processes",
            "abstract": "This thesis deals with different aspects of spatial interpolation and prediction of random fields. In the case of Gaussian random fields, best linear predictors and conditional distributions are well-known, provided that the mean and covariance structure of the random field are given. For parametric estimation of the covariance function from data, we consider the flexible class of Whittle-Mat\u00e9rn kernels. We introduce new estimators making use of connections between interpolation techniques in spatial statistics and numerical analysis. Besides the class of Gaussian random fields, we also consider max-stable random fields. Here, we put special emphasis on Brown-Resnick processes which occur as limits of maxima of Gaussian processes. As finite approximations of Brown-Resnick processes based on the definition do not reproduce stationarity, we give alternative representations allowing for new simulation techniques which we analyse in a simulation study. Compared to unconditional simulation, prediction and conditional simulation for max-stable processes are still in the early stage of development. We present an algorithm for conditional sampling of max-stable processes with a mixed moving maxima representation based on the Poisson point process structure of these processes. Under some additional assumptions we derive exact formulae for processes on the real axis. The results are compared to other algorithms. Finally, we apply the same techniques to extremal Gaussian and Brown-Resnick processes ...",
